Note:
This file implements aggressive dead code elimination (DCE) over MIR.

The algorithm is the classic mark-sweep:
- MARK: seed a worklist with every instruction that has an OBSERVABLE EFFECT
  or is required for control flow - stores, calls (direct and indirect),
  invokes, returns, throws, branches, jumps, switches, atomics, vector stores,
  the exception-handling band, debug-value records, and any operation that can
  TRAP at runtime (integer divide / modulo, whose result must be computed even
  when unused so the trap is preserved). Volatile loads are also critical: a
  volatile load's side effect is the memory access itself.
- PROPAGATE: drain the worklist; for each live instruction, mark the defining
  instruction of every value it USES as live (data dependencies), reaching a
  fixed point.
- SWEEP: delete every instruction that was never marked live, walking each
  block's instruction list backward so index removal is safe, and re-syncing
  the block's cached instruction_count.

Pure value computations (arithmetic, bitwise, comparisons, casts, copies,
loads of non-volatile memory, allocas, phis) whose results are never consumed
by a live instruction are eliminated. The pass preserves SSA form: it only
removes definitions whose results have no live use, so no use is left dangling.

Entry point: run_aggressive_dce_pass(optimizer_context) - reads the CFG at
context offset 0, accumulates the deletion count into the context's counter at
offset 40, and returns the number of instructions deleted.
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: IMPORTS
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir.runa" as MIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir_nodes.runa" as MIRNodes
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/cfg.runa" as CFG
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/ordered_map.runa" as OMap
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DEFINITION MAP - value id -> defining instruction
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "build_def_map" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Builds the pass-local definition map: SSA value id -> defining instruction
    pointer. SSA construction does not materialize MIRValue use/def lists
    (Wave 4), so the instruction stream is the only authoritative def source,
    and integer keys mandate an ordered map (collections/dictionary
    string-hashes integer keys and crashes - Wave 3). One O(I) scan converts
    every later "who defines this used value?" probe in the backward marking
    phase into an O(1) omap_get; a value id ABSENT from the map is defined
    outside any block (a function parameter or external constant) and has no
    defining instruction to mark.
    @End Reasoning

    Let def_map be proc omap_create from OMap
    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return def_map
    End If

    Let blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from CFG with cfg_ptr
    If blocks is equal to 0:
        Return def_map
    End If
    Let block_count be proc length from List with blocks

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
        If block is not equal to 0:
            Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block
            If instructions is not equal to 0:
                Let inst_count be proc length from List with instructions
                Let i be 0
                While i is less than inst_count:
                    Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, i
                    If inst is not equal to 0:
                        Let value_id be proc get_mir_node_value_id from MIR with inst
                        If value_id is not equal to 0:
                            proc omap_set from OMap with def_map, value_id, inst
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set i to i plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If
        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return def_map
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CRITICALITY CLASSIFICATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "is_critical_instruction" that takes inst as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    An instruction is CRITICAL (a root of liveness) when it has an observable
    effect, is required for control flow, or can trap at runtime:

    - MIR_STORE (20201): writes memory.
    - MIR_STORE_FIELD (20204): writes memory.
    - MIR_CALL (20304) / MIR_CALL_INDIRECT (20305): conservatively assumed to
      have side effects (the IR carries no purity attribute on callees yet).
    - MIR_BRANCH (20301) / MIR_JUMP (20302) / MIR_SWITCH (20306): control flow.
    - MIR_RETURN (20303): function exit.
    - Atomic band (20500-20511): memory side effects and synchronization.
    - MIR_VECTOR_STORE (20611): writes memory.
    - Exception band (20700-20706): INVOKE transfers control and may have
      callee side effects; LANDINGPAD / RESUME / THROW define the unwind path.
    - Debug band (20800-20804): debug-value/location records must survive so
      debug info stays attached to the values it describes.
    - MIR_DIV (20005) / MIR_MOD (20006): may TRAP on a zero divisor, so the
      computation must be preserved even when its result is unused (a dead
      div is NOT trivially removable).

    A volatile MIR_LOAD (20200) is also critical, but that requires reading
    the is_volatile extended field, handled by the caller alongside the opcode
    test so this predicate stays a pure opcode classifier.

    Returns 1 when the opcode alone makes the instruction critical.
    @End Reasoning

    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst

    If opcode is equal to 20201:
        Return 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20204:
        Return 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20304:
        Return 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20305:
        Return 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20301:
        Return 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20302:
        Return 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20303:
        Return 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20306:
        Return 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20611:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: Integer divide / modulo can trap on a zero divisor
    If opcode is equal to 20005:
        Return 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20006:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: Atomic band
    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20500 and opcode is less than or equal to 20511:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: Exception band
    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20700 and opcode is less than or equal to 20706:
        Return 1
    End If
    Note: Debug band
    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20800 and opcode is less than or equal to 20804:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BACKWARD MARKING
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "mark_value_definition_live" that takes value_id as Integer, def_map as Integer, live_set as Integer, worklist as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Marks the instruction that DEFINES value_id as live and enqueues it for
    transitive marking, unless it is already live or has no in-function
    definition (a parameter / external constant, absent from def_map).
    @End Reasoning

    If value_id is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let defining_inst be proc omap_get from OMap with def_map, value_id
    If defining_inst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let already_live be proc omap_get from OMap with live_set, defining_inst
    If already_live is equal to 0:
        proc omap_set from OMap with live_set, defining_inst, 1
        proc append from List with worklist, defining_inst
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "mark_operands_live" that takes inst as Integer, def_map as Integer, live_set as Integer, worklist as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Marks the defining instruction of every value this instruction USES as
    live. Canonical use enumeration (OD-1) via CFG.get_instruction_used_values
    covers header operand slots and phi incoming values uniformly; the
    call-family argument list (MIR_CALL 20304, MIR_CALL_INDIRECT 20305,
    MIR_INVOKE 20700) holds additional uses in the List at extended offset 88,
    and the indirect callee is itself an SSA use at extended offset 80.
    @End Reasoning

    Let used_values be proc get_instruction_used_values from CFG with inst
    If used_values is not equal to 0:
        Let used_count be proc length from List with used_values
        Let u be 0
        While u is less than used_count:
            Let used_value be proc get from List with used_values, u
            proc mark_value_definition_live with used_value, def_map, live_set, worklist
            Set u to u plus 1
        End While
        proc list_destroy from List with used_values
    End If

    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst
    Let has_arg_list be 0
    If opcode is equal to 20304:
        Set has_arg_list to 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20305:
        Set has_arg_list to 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20700:
        Set has_arg_list to 1
    End If
    If has_arg_list is equal to 1:
        If opcode is equal to 20305:
            Let callee be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 80
            proc mark_value_definition_live with callee, def_map, live_set, worklist
        End If
        Let arguments be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 88
        If arguments is not equal to 0:
            Let arg_count be proc length from List with arguments
            Let a be 0
            While a is less than arg_count:
                Let arg_value be proc get from List with arguments, a
                proc mark_value_definition_live with arg_value, def_map, live_set, worklist
                Set a to a plus 1
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MAIN PASS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "optimize_aggressive_dce" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Mark-sweep dead code elimination over one function's CFG. Returns the
    number of instructions deleted.

    PHASES:
    1. Build the def map (value id -> defining instruction).
    2. MARK: seed the live set + worklist with every critical instruction
       (observable effect / control flow / trapping op / volatile load).
    3. PROPAGATE: drain the worklist, marking the defining instruction of
       every used value live, to a fixed point.
    4. SWEEP: delete every unmarked instruction (backward per block so index
       removal is safe) and re-sync each block's instruction_count cache.

    SSA preservation: only definitions with no live use are removed, so no
    live instruction is left with a dangling operand.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The live set is an integer/pointer-keyed ordered map (instruction pointer
    -> 1) - dictionary string-hashing of pointer keys crashes at runtime
    (Wave 3). The worklist is a List used as a stack. Volatile-load
    criticality reads the MIRLoad is_volatile extended field at offset 104.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(N) mark seeding + O(uses) backward propagation (each instruction is
    enqueued at most once) + O(N) sweep, so the pass is linear in program
    size. DCE is re-run after every transformation that can render
    instructions dead (constant folding, copy propagation, SCCP).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Operates purely on compiler-internal MIR. The CFG pointer may be null
    (guarded). Trapping operations and volatile loads are never removed, so
    the pass cannot change observable behavior; the worst case on malformed IR
    is a missed elimination, never an unsafe write.
    @End Security_Scope

    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from CFG with cfg_ptr
    If blocks is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let block_count be proc length from List with blocks

    Let def_map be proc build_def_map with cfg_ptr
    Let live_set be proc omap_create from OMap
    Let worklist be proc list_create from List

    Note: --- Phase 2: MARK critical roots ---
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, i
        If block is not equal to 0:
            Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block
            If instructions is not equal to 0:
                Let inst_count be proc length from List with instructions
                Let j be 0
                While j is less than inst_count:
                    Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, j
                    If inst is not equal to 0:
                        Let is_critical be proc is_critical_instruction with inst
                        If is_critical is equal to 0:
                            Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst
                            If opcode is equal to 20200:
                                Let load_is_volatile be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 104
                                If load_is_volatile is not equal to 0:
                                    Set is_critical to 1
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                        If is_critical is equal to 1:
                            Let already be proc omap_get from OMap with live_set, inst
                            If already is equal to 0:
                                proc omap_set from OMap with live_set, inst, 1
                                proc append from List with worklist, inst
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: --- Phase 3: PROPAGATE liveness backward to a fixed point ---
    While proc length from List with worklist is greater than 0:
        Let live_inst be proc list_remove from List with worklist, 0
        proc mark_operands_live with live_inst, def_map, live_set, worklist
    End While

    Note: --- Phase 4: SWEEP unmarked instructions ---
    Let removed_count be 0
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, i
        If block is not equal to 0:
            Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block
            If instructions is not equal to 0:
                Let inst_count be proc length from List with instructions
                Let j be inst_count minus 1
                While j is greater than or equal to 0:
                    Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, j
                    If inst is not equal to 0:
                        Let is_live be proc omap_get from OMap with live_set, inst
                        If is_live is equal to 0:
                            proc list_remove from List with instructions, j
                            Set removed_count to removed_count plus 1
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set j to j minus 1
                End While
                Note: Re-sync the block's cached instruction_count (offset 24)
                Let remaining be proc length from List with instructions
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 24, remaining
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc omap_destroy from OMap with def_map
    proc omap_destroy from OMap with live_set
    proc list_destroy from List with worklist

    Let removed_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with removed_count
    Display "dce: eliminated " joined with removed_str joined with " dead instructions"

    Return removed_count
End Process

Process called "run_aggressive_dce_pass" that takes optimizer_context as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Pass-manager-facing entry point invoked by mir_optimizer.runa's
    optimize_dead_code_elimination wrapper. The OptimizerContext carries the
    CFG at offset 0 and a running deletion counter at offset 40. We read the
    CFG, run the mark-sweep, fold the per-pass elimination count into the
    shared counter, and return the count so the orchestrator can detect
    fixed-point convergence (zero eliminations -> no further passes needed).

    Returns the number of instructions eliminated.
    @End Reasoning

    If optimizer_context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with optimizer_context, 0
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let eliminated be proc optimize_aggressive_dce with cfg

    Let current_deleted be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with optimizer_context, 40
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with optimizer_context, 40, current_deleted plus eliminated

    Return eliminated
End Process

Process called "should_run_dce" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Gate predicate. Refuses null or empty CFGs; otherwise always worth running
    (dead computations appear in nearly every function and every prior pass
    can expose more).

    Returns 1 when the pass should run, 0 otherwise.
    @End Reasoning

    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from CFG with cfg_ptr
    If blocks is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let block_count be proc length from List with blocks
    If block_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "get_dce_pass_name" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Short pass name for the pass-manager registration table and log header.
    @End Reasoning

    Return "Aggressive Dead Code Elimination"
End Process

Process called "get_dce_pass_description" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Human-readable pass description for diagnostics and pass-list rendering.
    @End Reasoning

    Return "Mark-sweep DCE: removes pure unused definitions, preserving effects and traps"
End Process
